Title: 25 Description of photographs - Bontoc Igorot
Description.note: [Typograph descriptions of photographs]|~|31. --Three Bontoc Igorot women returning from the fields from the fields with ca[?]otes. Camotes form the chief article of diet of the people of this tribe. Note the erect carriage of the woman at the right.32. -- Group of Bontoc Igorot women ready for a footrace.33.-- Young Bontoc Igorot woman of Talubir.34. --Group of Igorots standing on a bridge awaiting the arrival of the Secretary of the Interior. This bridge, which crosses a branch of the Rio Chico, is necessarily placed at a great height above the water to prevent its being carried away by one of the tremendous floods to which this river and all others in the mountains of northern Luzon, are subject. In the great typhoon of October 1909, water came within two feet of the floor of the bridge.35. -- Bontoc Igorot women of Tucucan. The one at the left is holding a piece of cotton cloth won an a prize in the foot-race in which the women shown in photograph 32 were about to engage.

Title: 41 Description of photographs
Description.note: 56. --Young Ifugao girl, the daughter of Matang, one of the famous fighting chiefs of Mayoyao. Note the typical brass wire or-naments on her arms, also the neck ornament made of plates of mother of pearl.57. --An Ifugao woman weaving. The women of this tribe are quite skillful in the use of the primitive loom shown in this photograph, producing narrow strings of strong, well-woven cotton cloth.58. --Group of Ifugaos coming into Mayoyao to meet the Secretary of the Interior. The chief at the head of the line carries in his right hand a cane as a symbol of office, and in his left a white chicken which he will present as a gift of friendship. The two men immediately behind him bear jars of bubud, a fermented drink made from rice, in which the Ifugao are somewhat prone to over-indulge on festive oc-casions. The last man has on his shoulder a young pig tied so tightly that it cannot move.59. --An Ifugao orator at Quiarigan. The Ifugao men are born speechmakers. This particular individual is addressing a large audience which does not show in the photograph. He doubtless began his remarks by informing his hearers that he was a very wealthy man and had many pigs and chickens.60. --A primitive sugar cane mill. Mills of this type are common-ly used by Bontoc Igorotaa and Tingians. They are less common among the Ifugaos and Kalingas. The people of all these tribes ordinarily employ sugar cane juice in making [?], more rarely it is boiled to produce sugar.|~|[Typograph]

Title: 47 Description of photographs 66-70
Description.note: 66. --Panoramic view at Banaue. To the left and in the center are two small Ifugao villagers. At the right is a lvel plot of ground on which now stand the public buildings of the sub-province of Ifugao. When this photograph was taken temporary building were in process of construction.67. --An Ifugao man and his wife, in wedding custom.68. --An old Ifugao headhunter, with some of the trophies of his prowess.69. --Mattan baskets. The people of Banaue are particularly skillful in weaving baskets of this type.70. --An Ifugao resting bench, called "tagabi." Benches of this sort are made from single logs and are very heacy. They are carved out in the forest and are then brought into the villages at great expense of labor and time. The possession of a "tagabi" is conclusive evidence that the owner is a member of the so-called Ifugao "nobility."

Title: 50 Photograph descriptions 71-75
Description.note: [typograph]71. --Gabi, a Benguet Igorot girl of Pico, showing the typical dress of the women of this tribe.72. --Typical group of Benguet Igorots. THe woman at the left and the man at the right have on their backs the carrying baskets known as "chuggees." The two men at the center are leading dogs which will doubtless soon be eaten. The Ben-guet Igorots consider dog meat a great luxury.73. --Jesuit rest house on top of Mount Mirador at Baguio. The first and second story rooms at the left of this building are occupied by government metorological and sce[?] in-struments. The Jesuit orcer allows the rooms to be used observatory purposes free of charge.74. --The dog market at Baguio.75. --A tree fern.

Description.note: [typograph description of photograph 76]76. --Officers connected with the Mountain Province. From left to right they are:Wm. S. Miller, Lieutenant Governor of Lepanto;Captain H.J. Hunt, Philippines Constabulary;J.B. Early, Lieutenant Governor of Amburayan;C.F. Olson, Secretary-Treasurer, of the province;Wm. F. Pack, Governor of the province;Dean C. Worcester, Secretary of the Interior;Walter F. Halo, Lieutenant governor of Kalinga;Jeff D. Gailman, Lieutenant Governor of Ifugao;Samuel F. Kamo, SUpervisor of the province;Elmer E. Eckman, Lieutenant Governor of Benguet; and John G. Evans, Lieutenant governor of Bontoc.Sr. [?]lass Villamor, Lieutenant Governor of Apayao, is absent.John H. Evans has since been made governor of Apayao, is absent.John H. Evans has since been made Governor of Palawan and J.B. Early has been trasnferred to Bontoc.

Description.note: 102. --Typical Mountain Province trail running thorugh the pine-trees.103. --Heavy rockwork on the Mountain Trail. Just beyond the point where the Igorot atan[?] there is a straight drop of about 700 feet.104. --Igorot [?] at work. |One of the reasons that it had been [?] to construct the Mountain Province trail as cheaply is that the will man are employed as a laborors and are trained as [?] of dirt gang[?], pow-dorzon etc.105.-- An Igorot climbing a tree-[?]. Tree[?] forty foot or more in height are [?] alone the trail in the Mountain Province.106. --[?] view of a portion of the country through which runs the new trail from Corvantos to Pontoo, over which the party of the Secretary of War passed; the Malayan Range in the left background of the right-hand print, the point where the Tagulin Trial runs just beyong the long ridges shown in the foreground. The curious mountain which has apparently been the result of an up-thrust will be seen in the right of the left-hand print. Immediately back [?] to the left of it is Mt.
